'','Eden_01a','','inherit','open','closed','','eden_01a','','','2015-10-16 18:39:58','2015-10-16 18:39:58','',3056,'https://inventiondevfund.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/Eden_01a.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(3092,2,'2015-11-17 03:21:17','2015-11-17 03:21:17','<h2>The IDF Group at Intellectual Ventures Opens Multimillion-dollar Next-Generation Technology Development Centre in Singapore</h2>\r\n<strong>Singapore, 17 November 2015</strong> – The Invention Development Fund (IDF), part of the Intellectual Ventures family of investment funds, today announced a multimillion-dollar investment in a new Technology Development Centre located in Singapore. The Centre enables IDF to prototype inventions from its 10,000-strong global invention network and translate them into valuable new products, businesses models, and spin-out or venture companies. By developing next generation products and companies that create new jobs and sources of growth for Singapore, the Centre aims to propel Singapore’s position as a global hub for innovation.\r\n\r\n“Today’s most pressing business challenges require organizations to look beyond their own R&amp;D resources to develop ideas more rapidly and accelerate time to market,” said Scott Needham, General Manager, Technology Development Centre, IDF. “By partnering with IDF through the new Centre, organizations can get to the future faster through a managed open innovation environment that utilizes external technology and expertise to accelerate the innovation process and drive transformation while minimizing risk.”\r\n\r\nIDF’s new Centre will be staffed by a team of engineers, specialists with multidisciplinary backgrounds, and managers with business and technical expertise. They will identify promising inventions and work with local partners to develop new prototypes and carry out additional scientific and technical testing. For organizations, this means substantially reduced risk as they can access, develop, and take to market an invention and accompanying prototype that has been refined and tested by the Centre.\r\n\r\n“We are glad that Intellectual Ventures has chosen Singapore as a strategic partner to spearhead their innovation strategy and business in Asia,” said Mr. Beh Kian Teik, Executive Director, i3, Singapore Economic Development Board (EDB). “The Technology Development Centre is a unique combination of inventorship and entrepreneurship, which enhances the creation of new products and business models. This creates good value for the local industry and society and will continue strengthening Singapore’s position as a global innovation hub.”\r\n\r\nThe Technology Development Centre investment is part of IDF and Intellectual Ventures\' commitment to developing, protecting, and distributing inventions from thousands of inventors around the world – from emerging countries like China and India to established invention leaders like the United States and Japan. By partnering with leading inventors, collaborating with pioneering companies, and investing both expertise and capital in the process of invention, IDF aims to bring open innovation to today’s most pressing business and technical challenges. By founding the new Centre in Singapore, Intellectual Ventures hopes to turbocharge technological progress, create new businesses, and accelerate positive change across the region.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">--- End ---</p>\r\n<strong>About Intellectual Ventures and Invention Development Fund</strong>\r\nFounded in 2000, Intellectual Ventures (IV) is a privately-held invention capital company. With more than US$6 billion committed capital and more than 40,000 IP assets in active monetization programs, IV owns one of the world’s largest and fastest-growing intellectual property portfolios, which it licenses to the world’s most innovative companies. Investors include a mix of Fortune 500 companies, individuals, and institutions.\r\n\r\nThe Invention Development Fund (IDF) was established in 2007 as a new part of the Intellectual Ventures family of Investment Funds focused on building a global inventor network. IDF invents on behalf of its many customers in a variety of industries, ranging from huge multinational food and beverage or credit card companies to startups and regional SMEs. With employees in localized offices around the globe, IDF builds relationships with its closely-curated global network of more than 10,000 invention network members and more than 400 research institutions, universities, and companies. For more information about IDF, visit www.inventiondevfund.com.\r\n\r\n<strong>For media queries, please contact</strong>\r\nFlorence Mahon\r\nBurson-Marsteller for Invention Development Fund\r\nTel: +65 6671 3218\r\nEmail: florence.mahon@bm.com\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','The IDF Group at Intellectual Ventures Opens Multimillion-dollar Next-Generation Technology Development Centre in Singapore','','publish','open','open','','singapore-technology-development-centre','','','2016-05-25 11:18:29','2016-05-25 18:18:29','',0,'https://inventiondevfund.com/?p=3092',0,'post','',0),(3093,1,'2015-11-17 03:14:00','2015-11-17 03:14:00','','Logo-Transparent','','inherit','open','closed','','logo-transparent','','','2015-11-17 03:14:00','2015-11-17 03:14:00','',3092,'https://inventiondevfund.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/Logo-Transparent.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(3095,1,'2015-11-17 03:21:10','2015-11-17 03:21:10','','Intellectual-Ventures-logo2','','inherit','open','closed','','intellectual-ventures-logo2','','','2015-11-17 03:21:10','2015-11-17 03:21:10','',3092,'https://inventiondevfund.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/Intellectual-Ventures-logo2.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(3096,1,'2015-11-17 03:21:54','2015-11-17 03:21:54','','Intellectual-Ventures-logo-3','','inherit','open','closed','','intellectual-ventures-logo-3','','','2015-11-17 03:21:54','2015-11-17 03:21:54','',3092,'https://inventiondevfund.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/Intellectual-Ventures-logo-3.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(3099,2,'2015-11-24 22:36:57','0000-00-00 00:00:00','The New South Wales (NSW) State Government in Australia announced today it is awarding a grant of AUD$1.59M to take an orthopaedic spine-repair device from the research lab into human clinical trials. The device has been developed under a partnership between the Invention Development Fund (IDF) of Intellectual Ventures, and the University of News South Wales (UNSW) in Sydney.  Over the past three years, IDF has already provided AUD$2.3M in funding to UNSW to assist in early stage research, development, and design of the device to get it ready for trialing in humans. This new government grant now enables the next stage of research.  The device offers the potential to improve the success rate for spine fusion surgery, aiming for improved recovery rates and lower costs to patients and the health care system overall.\r\n\r\n(Full news release below)\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<strong>UNSW invention set to revolutionise back surgery</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>UNSW Australia invention expected to transform spinal fusion surgery will start human trials next year</li>\r\n	<li>Device targets chronic back pain, the most common reason for pain and disability in people aged under 50.</li>\r\n	<li>Trials made possible through $1.59m in funding from the NSW Government’s Medical Device Fund .</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nA revolutionary new spinal fusion device that is simpler and cheaper than existing technology and avoids the need for more invasive surgery and bone grafts will enter human trials next year, UNSW Australia researchers say.\r\n\r\nUNSW researchers and surgeons anticipate the innovative Thru-Fuze™ medical device will transform spinal fusion surgery, which is used when conservative therapies such as physical therapy, medication and injections have failed.\r\n\r\nThe human trials, which are expected to begin at the Prince of Wales Hospital, Sydney in late 2016, have been made possible through $1.59m in funding from the NSW Government’s Medical Device Fund.\r\n\r\nOne of the goals of spinal fusion is to stabilise the spine to prevent the extraneous movement that causes back pain. Chronic back pain from spinal disorders or degenerative disc disease is a major public health issue around the world and is the most common reason for pain and disability in people aged under 50.\r\n\r\nProfessor Bill Walsh, surgical device inventor and Director of Surgical and Orthopaedic Laboratories at UNSW, said the device will allow faster, simplier surgery with minimal radiation exposure compared to current methods.\r\n\r\n“Existing methods of spinal fusion use rod or cage systems that require screws to be drilled into the spine and a painful bone graft harvested, which is the material used to form the bridge and obtain the fusion between the vertebrae in the spine,” Professor Walsh said.\r\n\r\n“These systems are very costly, difficult and time consuming to implant and they also have relatively variable rates of fusion success.”\r\n\r\n“Existing methods rely on the bone to make its way right across the vertebrae and it can take up to a year to find out if the surgery has been a success.\r\n\r\nNon-union, or failure to achieve a solid fusion, has been reported in over 50% of patients using existing methods of spinal fusion,” he said.\r\n\r\nThe Thru-Fuze™ device is innovative because it stabilises the spine without the need for a bone graft.\r\n\r\nPre-clinical and laboratory testing in animal models by Professor Walsh’s team has shown fusion of bone on and through the device after it is placed between vertebrae, resulting in rapid ‘biomechanical’ fixation.\r\n\r\n“Over time, the device then acts as a bridge between the adjacent vertebrae for additional bone to grow across, fusing the adjacent vertebrae together, bone to bone,” Professor Walsh said.\r\n\r\nUNSW Innovations introduced the venture capital firm, Intellectual Ventures, as a potential partner and helped secure funding of $2.3 million from the company. The funding allowed the UNSW team to engage global industrial experts, including Dr Andy Carter and Orchid Design USA, in the research and development phase of the product.\r\n\r\nThe new funding comes on top of $2.3m that has already been invested in the development of the device by Intellectual Ventures, a private equity company that invests in invention globally . That funding allowed the UNSW team to engage global industrial experts, including Dr Andy Carter and Orchid Design USA, in the research and development phase of the product. Intellectual Ventures has exclusively licensed the device from UNSW as part of an ongoing partnership with UNSW to source inventions to commercialise.\r\nDevice co-inventor Dr Matthew Pelletier, from UNSW’s Prince of Wales Clinical School, said the team had so far successfully navigated the “valley of death” between the creation of the medical device and its commercialisation. Patents for the technology have also been filed in Australia, Europe, China and the United States.\r\n\r\nNeurosurgeon and Conjoint Lecturer with UNSW’s Prince of Wales Clinical School, Dr Ralph Mobbs, who will lead the human trials, says the potential of the device is significant.\r\n\r\n“New technologies such as the Thru-Fuze™ are of paramount importance, as surgeons strive to deliver better patient outcomes with less invasive and more effective implant and prostheses options.”\r\n\r\nThe Thru-Fuze™ device was one of three medical devices to receive funding from NSW Health’s Medical Device Fund, announced this evening by the NSW Minister of Health, Jillian Skinner.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"># # #</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nUNSW Media Office contact:\r\nDan Wheelahan\r\n02 9385 1933, 0435 930 465\r\n<a href=\"mailto:d.wheelahan@unsw.edu.au\">d.wheelahan@unsw.edu.au</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','IDF partnership with UNSW leads to AUD$1.59M Government grant for further development of innovative orthopaedic device.','','draft','open','open','','unsw-back-surgery-innovation','','','2015-11-24 22:36:57','2015-11-24 22:36:57','',0,'https://inventiondevfund.com/?p=3099',0,'post','',0),(3101,2,'2015-11-24 01:50:58','2015-11-24 01:50:58','','UNSW_Logo_01','','inherit','open','closed','','unsw_logo_01','','','2015-11-24 01:51:25','2015-11-24 01:51:25','',3099,'https://inventiondevfund.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/UNSW_Logo_01.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(3102,2,'2015-11-24 22:31:33','2015-11-24 22:31:33','','UNSW_Banner_01','','inherit','open','closed','','unsw_banner_01','','','2015-11-24 22:31:33','2015-11-24 22:31:33','',0,'https://inventiondevfund.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/UNSW_Banner_01.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(3103,1,'2015-11-24 22:42:20','2015-11-24 22:42:20','[vc_row full_width=\"stretch_row_content_no_spaces\" padding_bottom=\"-80\" margin_bottom=\"-80\"][vc_column offset=\"vc_hidden-lg vc_hidden-md vc_hidden-sm\"][vc_single_image image=\"3152\"][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row full_width=\"stretch_row\" padding_top=\"60\" padding_bottom=\"40\" font_color=\"#4d4d4d\" css=\".vc_custom_1441042963431{background-color: #f6f6f6 !important;}\"][vc_column][vc_row_inner css_animation=\"top-to-bottom\" css_animation_delay=\"200\" css=\".vc_custom_1440799572005{margin-top: 70px !important;margin-bottom: 70px !important;}\"][vc_column_inner width=\"1/12\"][vc_column_text]\r\n[/vc_column_text][/vc_column_inner][vc_column_inner width=\"10/12\"][vc_column_text]\r\n<h1 style=\"text-align: center; text-transform: uppercase;\">Help Conquer a<strong> <span style=\"color: #ff940e;\">Major Challenge</span></strong></h1>\r\n[/vc_column_text][vc_text_separator title=\"For New Fast Moving Consumer Goods\" color=\"custom\" border_width=\"2\" el_width=\"50\" accent_color=\"#1a7f8e\" el_class=\"reduce-margin-top\"][/vc_column_inner][vc_column_inner width=\"1/12\"][vc_column_text]\r\n[/vc_column_text][/vc_column_inner][/vc_row_inner][vc_row_inner css_animati