2-21 00:15:52','',3346,'https://inventiondevfund.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/Current-Tech-Lacking.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(3382,1,'2016-02-22 19:31:22','2016-02-22 19:31:22','','Mike-Manion','','inherit','open','closed','','mike-manion-2','','','2016-02-22 19:31:22','2016-02-22 19:31:22','',3346,'https://inventiondevfund.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/Mike-Manion.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(3383,1,'2016-02-22 19:56:58','2016-02-22 19:56:58','','Mike-Manion-2','','inherit','open','closed','','mike-manion-2-2','','','2016-02-22 19:56:58','2016-02-22 19:56:58','',3346,'https://inventiondevfund.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/Mike-Manion-2.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(3385,1,'2016-02-22 20:14:50','2016-02-22 20:14:50','','Invention-Suggestions','','inherit','open','closed','','invention-suggestions-3','','','2016-02-22 20:14:50','2016-02-22 20:14:50','',3346,'https://inventiondevfund.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/Invention-Suggestions.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(3387,5,'2016-02-25 03:43:03','2016-02-25 03:43:03','<hr />\r\n\r\nFollowing the recent IDF-Fraunhofer announcement, IAM magazine editor Joff Wild posted this article, providing additional perspective for the deal.  (Full article reposted here with permission.)\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<strong>The Intellectual Ventures invention fund teams up with Fraunhofer in major move into Europe</strong>\r\n\r\n18 February 2016 -- Joff Wild, IAM Magazine\r\n\r\nThe <a href=\"http://inventiondevfund.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Invention Development Fund</a> (IDF) of Intellectual Ventures has signed a joint venture agreement with Germany’s SET Technologies to develop and commercialise innovations in Germany and elsewhere. In a major coup for the new JV, it will partner with the <a href=\"http://www.fraunhofer.de/en.html\" target=\"_blank\">Fraunhofer Institutes</a> to work on a series of projects. I understand that three are already underway, relating to water technology, biometric sensors and life sciences. Details will be announced today (Thursday 18<sup>th</sup> February) at an event taking place in Berlin to be attended by, among others, IV co-founder Nathan Myhrvold and Fraunhofer president Reimund Neugebauer.\r\n\r\nFraunhofer-Gesellschaft is Europe’s leading applied research organisation, with a combined total of 67 institutes and research units at locations throughout Germany. It employs 24,000 people and has an annual research budget totalling more than €2.1 billion.\r\n\r\nFor its part, the IDF was established by IV in 2007 and currently has 75 employees and several hundred million dollars under management. Its remit is to invest in inventions. To date, the IDF has largely focused on establishing relationships and building a presence in North America and Asia. Among the 400 individuals and entities it is currently working with are Caltech, McGill University, Peking University and the Indian Institutes of Technology. It also has its own <a href=\"http://www.intellectualventureslab.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Invention Lab in Seattle</a> and the recently launched <a href=\"http://www.intellectualventures.com/insights/archives/intellectual-ventures-creates-technology-development-center-in-singapore/\" target=\"_blank\">Technology Development Centre in Singapore</a>.\r\n\r\nThis, however, is IDF’s first full-scale venture into Europe and was inspired, I have been told, by the fund’s <a href=\"http://www.iam-media.com/Blog/Detail.aspx?g=199dcbef-00dd-4663-8a7e-fd4c23d93956\" target=\"_blank\">involvement with Finnish company Raisio</a>. That partnership has proved to be “a big eye opener” as to what opportunities there are in this part of the world. According to IDF sources, the fund puts a lot of stock on being able to capture and develop inventions, no matter where they originate. “Clearly, amazing inventions come from Europe too,” I was told. “Our customers at IDF are also increasingly multi-national and were probably less than impressed that we called ourselves the “world’s biggest managed invention network” but didn’t have a presence in Europe.”\r\n\r\nIt has taken about two years to get to today’s news, with detailed negotiations over that time focusing on the specific projects to be undertaken and the structure of how the parties would work together. Now that these have been resolved, both IDF and Fraunhofer have a headline grabbing and potentially exciting arrangement on their hands.\r\n\r\nLast <a href=\"http://www.intellectualventures.com/news/legal-updates/intellectual-ventures-files-infringement-complaint-against-versicherungskam\" target=\"_blank\">August</a> and <a href=\"http://www.intellectualventures.com/news/legal-updates/intellectual-ventures-files-infringement-complaints-against-two-telecom-com\" target=\"_blank\">September</a> IV filed its first patent litigation suits in Germany, and followed up with <a href=\"http://www.intellectualventures.com/news/legal-updates/intellectual-ventures-files-additional-complaints-in-germany\" target=\"_blank\">further action last month</a>. IDF’s hook-up with Fraunhofer will inevitably lead to questions about whether we can now expect to see more activity of a similar kind in Europe – especially with the unitary patent and the Unified Patent Court on their way. My understanding, though, is that there is absolutely no connection. The IDF is run as an independent entity within IV and does not link its strategy to what other parts of the business may be doing. “This was absolutely not part of the calculus we used to decide to come to Europe,” I was told. “For us, it is really about finding where the best inventors are - and Fraunhofer has 20,000 of them - and where the companies that want to access our services and expertise are. Increasingly, our customers are literally everywhere, or want to be. So we had to be able to support them everywhere too.”\r\n\r\nThe IDF remains a relatively small part of the overall IV offering – which continues to be dominated by patent-based transactions. But over recent years it has garnered a lot of attention, not only as a result of its partnership with Raisio, but also thanks to a number of other ventures, including its successful <a href=\"http://www.iam-media.com/Blog/Detail.aspx?g=7a609227-6105-444a-9d86-e0c80b2e317b\" target=\"_blank\">roll-out of coffee flour company CF Holdings</a>.  While it is unlikely that there will be any shift in the IV balance of power in the near to medium future, it is no secret that the firm has found the going tough over recent years. With IDF, IV has a completely different story to tell and a very different business cycle to exploit. One or two blockbuster inventions and/or spin-outs, and the whole picture changes. Teaming up with the likes of Fraunhofer makes that possibility much more likely.\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nOriginal article posted here:\r\nhttp://www.iam-media.com/blog/Detail.aspx?g=912e8736-c804-40f7-9296-07538c53d35e\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','IAM blog repost:  IDF-Fraunhofer and more','','publish','open','open','','joff-wild-iam-article','','','2016-02-25 03:43:03','2016-02-25 03:43:03','',0,'https://inventiondevfund.com/?p=3387',0,'post','',0),(3388,5,'2016-02-25 02:59:55','2016-02-25 02:59:55','','Joff_iam_01b','','inherit','open','closed','','joff_iam_01b','','','2016-02-25 02:59:55','2016-02-25 02:59:55','',0,'https://inventiondevfund.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/Joff_iam_01b.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(3389,1,'2016-02-27 02:13:30','2016-02-27 02:13:30','','Market Predictability Hero Final copy','','inherit','open','closed','','market-predictability-hero-final-copy','','','2016-02-27 02:13:30','2016-02-27 02:13:30','',0,'https://inventiondevfund.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/Market-Predictability-Hero-Final-copy.mp4',0,'attachment','video/mp4',0),(3390,1,'2016-02-27 02:13:35','2016-02-27 02:13:35','','Market_Predictability_Hero_Final_copy','','inherit','open','closed','','market_predictability_hero_final_copy','','','2016-02